Germany's new military ship has been postponed again.
According to local media, the last frigate of the German Navy was to be commissioned in 2014 to replace the old Cold War war war ships, but it will not be until at least next year due to faulty systems and a surge in costs.
The commission of the Rheinland-Pfalz, the flagship of the new Baden-Württemberg-class frigates, has been postponed until the first half of 2019, according to Die Zeit newspaper citing a military spokesman.
The ship was due to join the Navy in 2014, but worrying issues following the delivery plagued the fate of the ambitious project.
The four Baden-Württemberg-class ships ordered by the Navy in 2007 will replace the old Bremen-class ships.
They will be equipped with a powerful cannon, a range of anti-aircraft and anti-ship missiles as well as some hidden technologies, such as radar, infrared and sound signatures.
Other important features include longer maintenance periods, as it should be possible to use the new frigates up to two years away from national ports.
However, the continuing delays mean that the innovative warships, which are said to allow Germany to project its power overseas, will become obsolete when they enter service, notes Die Zeit.
The unfortunate F-125 frigate made headlines last year when the German Navy officially refused to commission the ship and returned it to the Blohm & Voss shipyard in Hamburg.
It was the first time the Navy had returned a ship to a builder after delivery.
Little is known about the reasons for the return, but German media have noted a number of crucial software and hardware defects that rendered the ship useless if used on a combat mission.
The software deficiencies were particularly important as the Baden-Württemberg-class ships will be operated by a crew of about 120 sailors, barely half the staff of the oldest Bremen-class ships.
In addition, it was found that the ship was considerably overweight, which reduced its performance and limited the possibility for the Navy to add future upgrades.
The 7,000-tonne Rheinland-Pfalz is believed to be twice as heavy as the similar class of ships used by the Germans in World War II.
Apart from faulty hardware, the cost of the entire project (including crew training) is also becoming an important issue.
It appears to have reached 3.1 billion euros ($3.6 billion) from the initial 2.2 billion euros.
The problems involving the new frigates are becoming particularly important in the light of recent alarms about the reduction of German naval power.
At the beginning of the year, Parliamentary Commissioner for the Armed Forces, Hans-Peter Bartels, admitted that the Navy was actually short on ships capable of being deployed.
The official said that the issue has worsened considerably over time, since the old unarmed ships have not been replaced by new ships.
His regret is that none of the Baden-Württemberg-class frigates could join the Navy.
The National Trust spies on the secret lives of bats
New research on a Scottish Highland estate aims to reveal how bats use their eyesight to obtain food.
It is hoped that the findings will shed light on the behaviour of the only existing flying mammals and guide future conservation activities.
The National Trust for Scotland scientists' study will follow common bats and sopranos, as well as brown-eared bats and Daubenton bats at Inverewe Gardens in Wester Ross.
Special recorders will be placed in key locations around the property to track bat activity during the season.
The NHS staff and volunteers will also conduct mobile investigations using portable detectors.
The sound analyses recorded by an expert will determine the frequency of the bats' calls and how each species behaves.
A map of the habitats and a report will be produced to create a detailed scale-based picture of their behaviour.
Rob Dewar, a nature conservation consultant for the NTS, hopes the results can reveal which areas of habitat are most important for bats and how they are used by each species.
This information will help determine the benefits of habitat management work, such as grassland creation, and how best to maintain forests for bats and other related species.
The bat population in Scotland and the United Kingdom has declined considerably over the past century.
Bat species are at risk from construction and development work involving three-legged bats and habitat damage.
Wind turbines and lighting can also pose a threat, as can mosquito-killer paper and certain chemical treatments of building materials, in addition to domestic cat attacks.
Bats aren't really blind.
However, because of their nighttime hunting habits, their ears are more useful than their eyes when it comes to catching prey.
They use a sophisticated eco-location technique to spot insects and obstacles along their path.
LNTS, which is responsible for the care of over 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land in the country, takes bats very seriously.
Ten qualified experts regularly conduct investigations, inspect the trucks and sometimes perform rescue operations.
The organisation even set up Scotland's first bat-only reserve at Threave Estate in the Dumfries and Galloway region, which is home to eight of Scotland's ten bat species.
The head of the estate, David Thompson, says the property is the ideal territory.
We have a large bat area here in Threave, he said.
We have ancient buildings, many ancient trees and a good habitat.
But there is much about bats that we do not yet know, so the work we do here and on other properties will help us understand more about their growth needs.
It stresses the importance of controlling bats before carrying out maintenance within the property as it is possible that the unintentional destruction of a single maternal trident could kill up to 400 females and young, perhaps wiping out an entire local population.
Bats are protected and it is illegal to kill, harass, disturb or destroy their prey.
Elisabeth Ferrell, Scotland's head of the Bat Conservation Trust, encouraged the public to help.
He said: "We still have a lot to learn about our bats and for many of our species we don't know how their populations are going through it".
